So capital is NOT a constraint, only your mindset and ability to effectively deploy capital into growth is. 

Flip the switch on your Growth Mindset

Any startup in Web3 is an ambitious multi-decade play, it requires a lot of capital

But fortunately we have over-capitalisation ie more money than there are good startups in venture 

& an even more responsive feedback loop in secondary #crypto markets in response to growth

A #Web3 example of this is how the folks at @0xPolygon aggressively deploy capital into growth (sometimes through M&A) which drives token price, which grows the value of their treasury, which makes the cost of capital (and therefore growth) cheaper
By constantly raising and investing (well) in growth it’s franchise value grew and so the cost of raising more money was lower, meaning the ‘cost of capital’ was much lower than its competition.

What do I mean by that? 

Like Amazon throughout the 2000s its revolutionary vision for e-commerce was a multi-decade play, where it was (still is) continuously loss making as it invests in growth

Bezos understood better than most founders how Wall Street worked

The biggest mistake I see in #web3 is startups bootstrapping for too long OR slowing down spending on growth as runway reduces. 

Raise more, invest more. 

Winning in Web3 is almost always about aggressive growth at any cost. 

ie reducing the ‘cost of capital’
Just some casual cross portfolio ❤️

Thinking aloud here... 

What are your thoughts? 

Will the web continue to be ‘free’? 

If not advertising how will free be subsidised? 

What business models for #web3 do you see replacing free?

Now with Layer 2 and alternative paradigms like we are seeing with @polkadex or @flow_blockchain maybe every action isn’t onchain (with a cost) or they are negated by new business models that would allow things like ‘Free to Play’ in gaming through sponsored transactions
So with Web 3 and The Open #Metaverse it’s about offsetting the costs of entry and participation... ? 🤷‍♂️

What I think I mean by that is:

Web 2 = the web is ‘free’ only you pay with your data (and privacy) but have no stake in the value generated from it

Web 3 = onchain everything costs something but you can (maybe) earn more direct economic value back than you put in over time

Someone just asked me what’s the biggest challenge to #web3 adoption.. 

My reply (without too much thought) was; 

Making the general population shift from a ‘free’ Web to ‘pay to earn’

the rise of DeFi and a renewed interest in crypto and Web 3.

and working on helping them solve what was back then a hard theoretical problem.

when no one was really interested in token economies

What they were promising to do, to most people, felt so far into the future no one was interested 🔮

Like DeFi, #dCommerce will have its own highly composable stack of specialized protocols that aggregate & match supply with demand via automated market makers & various agents 🤖 

not just for capital 💰 but goods 📦 , and then enable their timely, affordable & safe fulfillment

Well @BosonProtocol is to #dCommerce what stable coins were to #DeFi. 

A foundational primitive that catalyses an ecosystem of possibility and innovation by solving the physical-to-digital problem of on-to-offchain commerce.
We are now in 2021, and whilst we have a maturing Web 3 stack that is both more usable and scalable, this future still has not happened. Why?

When considering @Amazon alone this is a trillion $ opportunity but increasingly it is also a social imperative for govts around the 🌍 to introduce more competition into The Web, better serve a long-tail of merchants & ultimately produce a more consumer centric economy.

(c) UX / Prime brokerage

(b) CeFi to DeFi Bridges

Traditional finance has amassed decades of complex legacy IT systems that are often antiquated and difficult for newer external technologies to directly integrate with. Requiring new bridges to be built between CeFi and DeFi.

(4) Accessibility Usability

(a) Administration: Accounting & Taxes

Accounting APIs that remove administrative burden of filing end of year tax returns of increasingly complex multi-protocol products that will put off many or limit their trading activity and frequency.

(d) Access Tokens

Access to digital vaults with collateral inside rather than a digital representation of collateral or a right (potentially a security)

NFTs could be access to underlying collateral and be burnt / consumed when used (rental or a trust arrangement)

(c) Multi-asset swaps

How do we swap STOs, CBDCs and crypto and vice versa? 

If NFTs can each carry wallet KYC & AML permissioning all assets can still co-exist in the same decentralised environment and be freely exchanged with one another in pairs or mixed into baskets

(b) Income bearing NFTs

The problem with #DeFi 1.0 yield, was the yield was not linked to actual income, rather a form of subsidised user acquisition and therefore unsustainable. 

we need income bearing instruments wrapped as NFTs (e.g. invoice factoring or SME wrapped debt)

(3) Collateralisation

(a) #NFT Commodities / Derivatives

Most institutions will only come into DeFi if there are assets they know, understand and can price such as real world commodities, derivatives or things like real estate via STOs and NFT synthetics

(e) Analytics & Fundamental Analysis

AI Analytics & Monitoring for CeFi to manage structural financial and compliance risks and activity around major dApps and associated assets inc. investment and usage behaviours and on-chain activity patterns around DeFi services

(d) Native Credit Scoring 

Attestation about assets via verifiable credentials linked to DIDs as NFTs a native onchain credit profile for credit scoring (augmented by staking & oracles for risk adjusted credit profiles)

(c) Trustful Oracles

For institutions to trust DeFi, automation via smart contracts, they need increased surety in oracles and their truthfulness to achieve compliant levels of reporting and security and resilience to manipulation.

(b) Administration / Custody

DIDs for permissioning of ‘organisation wallets’, containing digital portable credentials to confirm an orgs identity and verify the authority of employees / reps to act on behalf of the organisation

(2) Risk Management

Insurance / Reinsurance as #NFTs

DeFi needs a native form of insurance contract and mutualisation to minimise financial exposure to risk where it can’t be removed technically e.g. @NexusMutual

Insurance policies as NFT collateral for Reinsurance markets

(1) Compliance

'Decentralized KYC & AML' via reusable DIDs and verifiable credentials delivered through an open verifiable claims market which removes regulated counterparty requirements from the #DeFi Protocols

Lowering the barrier to institutional participation:

(1) Compliance

(2) Risk Management

(3) Collateralisation

(4) Accessibility & Usability

(5) Market Efficiencies

.. AI Lego for Money Lego (Open and accessible off-chain lego)

Complex off-chain logic + on-chain smart contract logic to proactively respond to external events (via oracles).

(4) Autonomous Economic Agents (AEAs)

Intelligent agent acting on owners behalf with limited to no interference whose goal is to generate economic value 

Allowing more complexity at smart contract logic and execution layer of DeFi 

+ AI Lego for Money Lego

DIDs = identifies any subject decoupled from centralized registries, identity providers, and certificate authorities.

VCs = exchange info with verified provenance and unchanged integrity

private data, transactions & compute

This mindset really is a win win

Im not saying I’ve mastered it but it’s a good mantra

Good for you

Good for the people around you

Good for wider society

In the UK / USA we are so brain washed with the ‘hard work’ hyper competitive mindset it at first feels like an affront

acknowledging the role of randomness / luck in your journey:

-is good for your mental health because you see failure as part of success some things fail despite hard work 

-helps you develop compassion & empathy which is less isolating

-makes a better world to enjoy success in

Im a venture capitalist, I believe in capitalism, I reward entrepreneurship, I am pretty middle of the road politically but..

the happiest & most successful founders I know acknowledge the role of luck / randomness alongside their hard work

That really shouldn’t be offensive

And it’s why American is on fire now 🔥 

It is the self justification of an historically unsustainable level of economic inequality

Statistically the last time it got this close we got the French Revolution

Success should be celebrated but it should also be understood because the ‘hard work narrative’ endemic in highly individuated meritocratic  societies like the US and UK leads to the highest levels of income and wealth inequality.

Remove the semantics and rhetoric and let’s explore the essence of what you are saying

My success is because of my hard work / that of my family

Your misfortune is because of your lack of hard work and / or that of your family

Right?

The Solution:

A marketplace that onboards entrepreneurs into Web 3, matches them with the right protocol at the right stage and accelerates them to the point to customers / and other investors the fact they have built on exotic Web 3 tech, let alone yours is abstracted away..

7. Direct or 3rd Party VC

If late stage your money is unlikely to affect technology adoption and too early without structured acceleration focused on customers and winning over the wider investor system is going to lead to high fail rate

6. Grants and hackathons do not cut it

This will at best deliver nice R&D and POCs but 99.9% not startups

5. No amount of capital solves this

Throwing money at startups might be a good treasury hedge but it will not = scale ups on your network

4. Let’s say you bribe them with some money to build on your protocol at the risk of a successful startup:

a) is that long term good for you and then
b) will they do the minimum to take your money and pivot 
c) does that make it more or less investible to other investors

3. Let’s assume you do find an entrepreneur that gets it AND a technical cofounder that also gets it then:

Why your protocol and why now? 

Making a given protocol core to a startups proposition early is currently a constraint, point of friction to adoption and risk

2. Entrepreneurs that get Web 3 even conceptually are sub 1% 

They do not technically understand the available stack or to find a technical partner that does because of (1)

1. Not even 99% of devs care about or understand The Web 3 Stack 

To many it’s not even a consideration. 

And even if they did 90% of devs are not going to create a successful startup, at least not alone

The unspoken truth in #crypto / #web3 is NOT ONE protocol has any real plan of how they hell they are going get..

A healthy startup 🚀 ecosystem building on their tech, that makes sustainable revenue 💵 & can close investment from other investors from Seed to Series B+💰

ZIP is an open-source tool for any group of networks, #DApps, #DAOs, developers or Enterprises to abstract the economic complexity away from building on Web3

ZIP is pegged to a universal unit of compute, i.e. the price of ledger ops in USD

The price to the user is stable, updating quarterly according to a forecasting model 

The margin on Actual Ledger Costs vs ZIP Sale Price acts like a Futures Market

The ZIP Token is a burn-&-mint model with 4 key elements:

1. Network tokens locked up as collateral
2. ZIP minted at market rate via oracle
3. Users purchase ZIP tokens (via DEX / fiat ramp)
4. When ZIP is spent, tokens are burned & collateral is used to cover the ledger cost

ZIP is a multi-network gas station backed by a collateral pool and enables:

- a single unit of account across multiple ledgers
- stable usage prices
- issuance of multi-network ‘cloud-credits’
- AWS-like pricing models that appeal to enterprises

#ZIP is an open source community project

The objective:

Develop a stable crypto commodity that abstracts the economic complexity for developers looking to

build, deploy & operate multi-network integrations

#Web3 adoption requires a way to solve for volatility in #crypto

both Gas & Token Price as digital commodities

We brought together a multidisciplinary team to solve the problem not just for one #blockchain but all of them

The solution is #ZIP

@SovrinID who are all looking to tap into this trillion dollar opportunity promising for the first time a form of identity native to the internet that doesn’t require anyone central party of intermediary.  

The beginning of #web3 is #SSI

And indeed it’s already begun: innovations in self sovereign identity user control and privacy have been making timely breakthroughs through initiatives like @SovrinID Sovrin who work in open collaboration with the biggest IT companies in the world like IBM and Microsoft..

In the new data economy the inverse will be true: by leveraging new innovations in decentralised technologies like blockchain it puts the user at the center, flipping the web and deconstructing a Facebook type platform model.
Where the current data economy is orientated towards the platform - the platform owns the data ,controls who can access it, and decides how to commodify it.
At the heart of this is what is referred to as self-sovereign identity #SSI where the end user is sovereign in the ownership of their identity and associated data. This will rewire the web.

SO WHAT NEXT? Fundamentally, there needs to be an entirely new data economy where data, its ownership and access is governed by the individual locally not on someone else’s servers so they can freely grant and revoke access on their own terms as they move around the web.

This will force a paradigm change where it is not just in the interest of customers and citizens that we gain greater control of our data and its security but the commercial interests of the companies we interact with.
As we saw with the combined $300m #GDPR fine for Marriot and British Airways recently regulators are serious about securing customer data and can levy up to 4% of global revenue for any business.
All these web platforms have achieved planetary scale through something called ‘the cloud’ which is effectively how they try (but fail) to store your data to make it secure.
but who now can both, no longer continue to freely extract value from it without our permission but also who can face huge fines for failing to effectively secure it.

But with new data laws like GDPR in Europe and increasing legal action in the US this treasure trove of data now increasingly looking like a liability rather than an asset. Not just for Facebook but for any company that has looked to commoditise our personal data..

giving what #CambridgeAnalytics themselves reported as over 70,000 data points on every US citizen whether they did or didn’t directly interact with their assets. This is off-the-shelf mass surveillance.
Facebook like #Apple has for several years let 3rd party companies that use its platform through apps unlock huge amounts of personal data about not just us but unwittingly also all of our contacts
@SovrinID one predicated on increasingly intrusive data extraction and user profiling for behavioural ‘modification’, be it advertising or political campaigning.

@SovrinID Facebook paying a record $5bn penalty in the US for data violations almost as a cost of business proves that the current data economy is totally broken. It really signals the beginning of the end for the business model of Facebook and its peers, indeed today’s whole web paradigm

At @OVioHQ we are preparing a bigger much more comprehensive report on how we think 2019 will unfold. But this is my personal 1st shot at a high-level primer on mood

So whilst the market will likely grow modestly the main investor opportunity is in the changing of the guard in the blue-chip top 10 as fragile players are replaced with better more robust teams and projects only just coming online that chose not to ICO

(not investment advice)
Combined this all brings a degree of stability to the market and should produce a slow upward trend, probably marked by a few bull runs as people misinterpret there being a return to frenzy 2018.

Early projects, where execution risk is greater, will be removed from public markets entirely and financed privately slowly removing the scam narrative and normalising failure to classic startup framing / ratios

Now exchanges are seeking approvals, classic VCs and family offices are the primary financiers, the markets will become more conservative, integrate and normalise.

As a consequence: Exchanges will begin to actively stop wash trading and manipulation reducing volatility.

Since the Ethereum #ICO there has been this rush with great hubris to do everything on-chain only possible whilst the community has been able to self-finance and existed in a regulatory grey frontier where leniency for all but the worst behaviour would likely be shown

The more I think about 2019 and see the month of Jan take shape the more I think there is a semi-bullish case to be made for #crypto
